Introduction

This document contains the source codes and corresponding execution results for exploring the factors impacting sleep quality among Chinese undergraduates in Jiangsu Province, including all detailed codes for tables, figures, and the adopted models (multiple linear regression, binary logistic regression, linear mixed model, logistic random effect regression) with standard diagnostics.

Data quality control

block.fun <- function(x,lower=T,upper=T){
  q1 <- quantile(x,0.25)
  q3 <- quantile(x,0.75)
  iqr <- q3 - q1
  if(lower){
    x[x <= q1 - 2 * iqr] <- q1 - 2 * iqr
  }
  if(upper){
    x[x >= q3 + 2 * iqr] <- q3 + 2 * iqr
  }
  return(x)
}

block <- wenjuan %>% select(age,height,weight,PSQI2,PSQI4) %>% map(block.fun) #%>% as_tibble
wenjuan <- wenjuan %>% mutate(
  age = block$age,
  height = block$height,
  weight = block$weight,
  PSQI2 = block$PSQI2,
  PSQI4 = block$PSQI4
)

Cronbach’s alpha

wenjuan.PSQI <- wenjuan %>% select(contains('PSQI'),-PSQI1,-PSQI2,-PSQI3,-PSQI4)  
alpha.PSQI <- wenjuan.PSQI %>% ltm::cronbach.alpha()
wenjuan.Mpai <- wenjuan %>% select(contains('Mpai')) 
alpha.MPAI <- wenjuan.Mpai %>% ltm::cronbach.alpha()
wenjuan.Cdrisc <- wenjuan %>% select(contains('Cdrisc')) 
alpha.CDRISC <- wenjuan.Cdrisc %>% ltm::cronbach.alpha()
cmb <- cbind(wenjuan.PSQI,wenjuan.Mpai) %>% cbind(.,wenjuan.Cdrisc) 
alpha.cmb <- cmb %>% ltm::cronbach.alpha()
cat("Cronbach's alpha of PSQI is:",alpha.PSQI$alpha,'\n')
cat("Cronbach's alpha of MPAI is:",alpha.MPAI$alpha,'\n')
cat("Cronbach's alpha of CD-RISC is:",alpha.CDRISC$alpha,'\n')
cat("Cronbach's alpha of the scale questionnaire is:",alpha.cmb$alpha)

Data processing

Generate some necessary variables, such as BMI, PSQI score, MPAI score, and CD-RISC score. And categorical variables are set as factors, ordinal variables are set as ordered factors.

mydata <- wenjuan %>% 
  mutate(
    gender = factor(case_when(gender == 1 ~ 'Male',
                              gender == 2 ~ 'Female'),
                    levels = c('Female','Male')),
    BMI = weight/((height/100)^2),
    MedicalMajor = factor(MedicalMajor),
    grade  = case_when(grade == 1 ~ 1,
                       grade == 2 ~ 2, 
                       grade == 3 ~ 3,
                       grade >  3 ~ 4),
    grade.ord = factor(grade,ordered = T),
    NativePlace = factor(case_when(NativePlace == 1 ~ 'Urban',
                                   NativePlace == 2 ~ 'Rural'),
                         levels = c('Rural','Urban')),
    OnlyChild = factor(case_when(OnlyChild == 1 ~ 'Yes',
                                 OnlyChild == 2 ~ 'No'),
                       levels = c('No','Yes')),
    FatherEducationLevel.ord = factor(case_when(
      FatherEducationLevel == 1 ~ 'MiddleSchoolOrLess',
      FatherEducationLevel == 2 ~ 'JuniorCollegeEducation',
      FatherEducationLevel == 3 ~ 'UndergraduateOrMore'),
      levels = c('MiddleSchoolOrLess','JuniorCollegeEducation','UndergraduateOrMore'),ordered = T),
    MotherEducationLevel.ord = factor(case_when(
      MotherEducationLevel == 1 ~ 'MiddleSchoolOrLess',
      MotherEducationLevel == 2 ~ 'JuniorCollegeEducation',
      MotherEducationLevel == 3 ~ 'UndergraduateOrMore'),
      levels = c('MiddleSchoolOrLess','JuniorCollegeEducation','UndergraduateOrMore'),ordered = T),
    MonthlyLivingExpense.ord = factor(case_when(
      MonthlyLivingExpense == 1 ~ '<1000',
      MonthlyLivingExpense == 2 ~ '1000-2000',
      MonthlyLivingExpense == 3 ~ '>2000'),
      levels = c('<1000','1000-2000','>2000'),ordered = T), 
    FamilyEconomicLevel.ord = factor(case_when(
      FamilyEconomicLevel == 1 ~ 'Good',
      FamilyEconomicLevel == 2 ~ 'Medium',
      FamilyEconomicLevel == 3 ~ 'Poor'),
      levels = c('Good','Medium','Poor'),ordered = T),
    smoking = factor(case_when(smoking == 1 ~ 'No',#'Never'
                               smoking == 2 ~ 'Yes',#'Occasional'
                               smoking == 3 ~ 'Yes'),#'Often'
                               levels = c('No','Yes')),
    drinking = factor(case_when(drinking == 1 ~ 'No',#'Never',
                                drinking == 2 ~ 'Yes',#'Occasional',
                                drinking == 3 ~ 'Yes'),#'Often'
                        levels = c('No','Yes')),
    PhysicalExercise.ord = factor(case_when(
      PhysicalExercise == 1 ~ 'OncePerMonth',
      PhysicalExercise == 2 ~ '1-3TimesPerWeek',
      PhysicalExercise == 3 ~ '4-7TimePerWeek'),
      levels = c('OncePerMonth','1-3TimesPerWeek','4-7TimePerWeek'),ordered = T),
    AcademicPressure.ord = factor(case_when(
      AcademicPressure == 1 ~ 'NotHave',
      AcademicPressure == 2 ~ 'Normal',
      AcademicPressure == 3 ~ 'Great'),
      levels = c('NotHave','Normal','Great'),ordered = T),
    EmploymentPressure.ord = factor(case_when(
      EmploymentPressure == 1 ~ 'NotHave',
      EmploymentPressure == 2 ~ 'Normal',
      EmploymentPressure == 3 ~ 'Great'),
      levels = c('NotHave','Normal','Great'),ordered = T),
    RoommateSleepsLate = factor(case_when(
      RoommateSleepsLate == 1 ~ 'Yes',
      RoommateSleepsLate == 2 ~ 'No'),levels = c('No','Yes')),
    NoisyDormitory = factor(case_when(
      DormitoryIsNoisy == 1 ~ 'Yes',
      DormitoryIsNoisy == 2 ~ 'No'),levels = c('No','Yes')),
    DormitoryLight = factor(case_when(
      DormitoryLightsAreBright == 1 ~ 'Bright',
      DormitoryLightsAreBright == 2 ~ 'Not Bright'),
      levels = c('Not Bright','Bright')),
    DormitoryHygiene = factor(case_when(
      DormitoryHygieneIsPoor == 1 ~ 'Poor',
      DormitoryHygieneIsPoor == 2 ~ 'Good'),levels = c('Good','Poor')),
    RelationshipWithClassmates.ord = factor(case_when(
      RelationshipWithClassmates == 1 ~ 'Harmonious',
      RelationshipWithClassmates == 2 ~ 'Ordinary',
      RelationshipWithClassmates == 3 ~ 'Poor'),
      levels = c('Harmonious','Ordinary','Poor'),ordered = T),
    AmativenessMatter = factor(case_when(
      AmativenessMatter == 1 ~ 'Never',
      AmativenessMatter == 2 ~ 'Ever',
      AmativenessMatter == 3 ~ 'BeingInlove'),
      levels = c('Never','Ever','BeingInlove')),
    PhysicalHealthStatus.ord = factor(case_when(
      PhysicalHealthStatus == 1 ~ 'Good',
      PhysicalHealthStatus == 2 ~ 'Ordinary',
      PhysicalHealthStatus == 3 ~ 'Bad'),
      levels = c('Good','Ordinary','Bad'),ordered = T),
    MentalHealthStatus.ord = factor(case_when(
      MentalHealthStatus == 1 ~ 'Good',
      MentalHealthStatus == 2 ~ 'Ordinary',
      MentalHealthStatus == 3 ~ 'Bad'),
      levels = c('Good','Ordinary','Bad'),ordered = T),
    ReceivedPsychologicalCounseling = factor(case_when(
      ReceivedPsychologicalCounseling == 1 ~ 'Yes',
      ReceivedPsychologicalCounseling == 2 ~ 'No'),levels = c('No','Yes')),
    zPSQIAshuimianzhiliang = PSQI6 - 1,
    PSQI2fenfuzhu = case_when(
      PSQI2 <= 15             ~ 0,
      PSQI2 >15 & PSQI2 <= 30 ~ 1,
      PSQI2 >30 & PSQI2 <= 60 ~ 2,
      PSQI2 >60               ~ 3),
    PSQI5afenfuzhu = PSQI5a - 1,
    zPSQIBrushuitime = PSQI2fenfuzhu + PSQI5afenfuzhu,
    zPSQICshuimiantime = case_when(
      PSQI4 > 7 ~ 0,
      PSQI4 > 6 & PSQI4 <= 7 ~ 1,
      PSQI4 > 5 & PSQI4 <= 6 ~ 2,
      PSQI4 <= 5 ~ 3),
    shangchuangtimefuzhu = if_else(
      hour(PSQI1) > 8 & hour(PSQI1) < 12,
      strptime(paste(hour(PSQI1) + 12,
                     minute(PSQI1),second(PSQI1),sep=':'),'%H:%M:%S'),
      if_else(hour(PSQI1) == 12,
              strptime(paste('00',minute(PSQI1),second(PSQI1),sep=':'),'%H:%M:%S'),
              strptime(PSQI1,'%H:%M:%S'))),
    shangchuangshijianfuzhu = if_else(
      hour(shangchuangtimefuzhu) >= 0 & hour(shangchuangtimefuzhu) <= 12 & day(shangchuangtimefuzhu) == day(Sys.Date()),
      shangchuangtimefuzhu + 60*60*24,as.POSIXct(shangchuangtimefuzhu)),
    qichuangtimefuzhu = strptime(paste(Sys.Date()+1,PSQI3),'%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S'),
    chuangshangshijianfuzhu = 
      as.numeric(difftime(qichuangtimefuzhu,shangchuangshijianfuzhu,units='hours')),
    shuimianxiaolvfuzhu =  PSQI4 / chuangshangshijianfuzhu,
    zPSQIDshuimianxiaolv = case_when(
      shuimianxiaolvfuzhu > 0.85 ~ 0,
      shuimianxiaolvfuzhu > 75 & shuimianxiaolvfuzhu <= 85 ~ 1,
      shuimianxiaolvfuzhu > 65 & shuimianxiaolvfuzhu <= 75 ~ 2, 
      shuimianxiaolvfuzhu <= 65 ~ 3),
    shuimianzhangaifuzhu = PSQI5b + PSQI5c + PSQI5d + PSQI5e + PSQI5f + PSQI5g 
    + PSQI5h + PSQI5i + PSQI5j - 9,
    zPSQIEshuimianzhangai = case_when(
      shuimianzhangaifuzhu == 0 ~ 0,
      shuimianzhangaifuzhu >= 1 & shuimianzhangaifuzhu <= 9 ~ 1,
      shuimianzhangaifuzhu >= 10 & shuimianzhangaifuzhu <= 18 ~ 2,
      shuimianzhangaifuzhu >= 19 & shuimianzhangaifuzhu <= 27 ~ 3),
    zPSQIFcuimianyaowu = PSQI7 - 1,
    zPSQIGrijiangongnengzhangai = case_when(
      PSQI8 + PSQI9 - 2 == 0 ~ 0,
      PSQI8 + PSQI9 - 2 >= 1 & PSQI8 + PSQI9 - 2 <= 2 ~ 1,
      PSQI8 + PSQI9 - 2 >= 3 & PSQI8 + PSQI9 - 2 <= 4 ~ 2,
      PSQI8 + PSQI9 - 2 >= 5 & PSQI8 + PSQI9 - 2 <= 6 ~ 3),
    zPSQI = pmap_dbl(across(.col=starts_with('zPSQI')),sum),
    zPSQI.cat = factor(case_when(zPSQI <= 7 ~ 'Good',
                                 zPSQI >  7 ~ 'Poor'),
                       levels = c('Good','Poor')),
    zCDRISC = pmap_dbl(across(.col = starts_with('Cdrisc')),sum),
    zCDRISCLiliang = pmap_dbl(across(.col = starts_with('CdriscLiliang')),sum),
    zCDRISCJianren = pmap_dbl(across(.col = starts_with('CdriscJianren')),sum),
    zCDRISCLeguan = pmap_dbl(across(.col = starts_with('CdriscLeguan')),sum),
    zMPAI = pmap_dbl(across(.col = starts_with('Mpai')),sum),
    zMPAIshikong = pmap_dbl(across(.col = starts_with('MpaiShikong')),sum),
    zMPAItaobi = pmap_dbl(across(.col = starts_with('MpaiTaobi')),sum),
    zMPAIjieduan = pmap_dbl(across(.col = starts_with('MpaiJieduan')),sum),
    zMPAIdixiao = pmap_dbl(across(.col = starts_with('MpaiDixiao')),sum)
  ) %>%  
  select(-ends_with('fuzhu'),-starts_with('Cdrisc'),-starts_with('PSQI'),
         -starts_with('Mpai'))

Define the function of showing mean and standard deviation (SD).

meansd <- function(x) {
  md = round(mean(x),digits = 2)
  sd = round(sd(x),digits = 2)
  return(paste0(md,'±',sd))
}

Use Levene’s test to check homoscedasticity among subgroups.

levene <- function(vb) {
  levene_test(zPSQI ~ vb,data = mydata)$p
}
leven.reslt <- mydata %>% 
  select(gender,grade.ord,MedicalMajor,NativePlace,OnlyChild,FatherEducationLevel.ord,MotherEducationLevel.ord,FamilyEconomicLevel.ord,MonthlyLivingExpense.ord,smoking,drinking,PhysicalExercise.ord,AcademicPressure.ord,RelationshipWithClassmates.ord,AmativenessMatter,PhysicalHealthStatus.ord,MentalHealthStatus.ord,ReceivedPsychologicalCounseling) %>% 
  map(levene) %>% unlist %>% round(.,digits = 4)

Display variables that satisfy homoscedaticity.

(leven.reslt.great <- leven.reslt[leven.reslt > 0.05]) 
##             MedicalMajor              NativePlace                OnlyChild 
##                   0.5698                   0.2255                   0.4485 
## MotherEducationLevel.ord 
##                   0.0590

Use t test or ANOVA to compare differences among subgroups. Post-hoc test is performed by Tukey’s method when homoscedasticity is satisfied, otherwise Games-Howell’s test.

ttest <- function(vb) {
  anova_summary(aov(mydata$zPSQI ~ vb))$p # t test or anova
}
mydata %>% select(all_of(names(leven.reslt.great))) %>% 
  map(ttest) %>% unlist
tukey_hsd(aov(mydata$zPSQI ~ mydata$MotherEducationLevel.ord))

welchtest <- function(vb) {
  welch_anova_test(mydata$zPSQI ~ vb, data = mydata)$p
}

The categorical and ordinal variables were described by frequency and constituent ratio, and their differences between groups were compared by Chi-square test.

a <- mydata %>% select(where(is.factor)) %>% map(.,table)
rate.tab.nomarg <- function(x){round(proportions(x)*100,2)}
rate.tab <- function(x){round(proportions(x,margin = 2)*100,2)}
a.rate <- a %>% map(.,rate.tab.nomarg)

Weighted multiple linear regression (Weighted MLR)

The standard regression diagnostics were processed with the following steps:

  1. Remove samples containing extreme values, including outliers, high leverage points, and influential points. The outliers were detected if the Bonferroni adjusted P value of the corresponding absolute studentized residuals was significant; the high leverage points were identified via the hat statistics; the influential points were determined by Cook’s distance.

  2. Check the independence of residuals with Durbin-Waston’s test.

  3. Detect the multicollinearity between explanatory variables through variance inflation factor (VIF).

  4. Detect the normality of residuals.

  5. Detect the homoscedasticity of residuals.

  6. Check linearity between dependent variable and explanatory variables.

reg.formula <- as.formula(
  zPSQI ~ gender + age + height + weight + BMI + zCDRISC + zMPAI + grade + MedicalMajor + NativePlace + OnlyChild + FatherEducationLevel + MotherEducationLevel + FamilyEconomicLevel + MonthlyLivingExpense + smoking + drinking + PhysicalExercise + AcademicPressure + EmploymentPressure + RelationshipWithClassmates + RoommateSleepsLate + NoisyDormitory + DormitoryLight + DormitoryHygiene + AmativenessMatter + PhysicalHealthStatus + MentalHealthStatus + ReceivedPsychologicalCounseling)
shuimian <- lm(formula = reg.formula, data = mydata)
performance::check_collinearity(shuimian)

There exists multicollinearity among weight, height and BMI. Thus, remove height and weight in the regression formula.

reg.formula <- update(reg.formula, . ~ . - height - weight)

Detect outliers and remove corresponding samples.

outlierResult <- car::outlierTest(shuimian)
if (outlierResult$bonf.p[1] < 0.05) {
  exclusionRows <- names(outlierResult[[1]])
  inclusionRows <- !(rownames(mydata) %in% exclusionRows)
  mydata.out    <- mydata[inclusionRows,]
  reg.last      <- lm(formula = reg.formula, data = mydata.out)
} else {reg.last <- shuimian;mydata.out <- mydata}

Remove high leverage points.

leverage.con <- names(which(hatvalues(reg.last) > 
                              3 * length(coefficients(reg.last))/length(fitted(reg.last))))
if (length(leverage.con) > 0) {
  exclusionRows <- leverage.con
  inclusionRows <- !(rownames(mydata.out) %in% exclusionRows)
  mydata.out    <- mydata.out[inclusionRows,]
  reg.last      <- lm(formula = reg.formula, data = mydata.out)
}

Remove influential points.

influential <- which(cooks.distance(reg.last) 
                     > 4/(nrow(mydata.out)-length(reg.last$coefficients)-2))
if (length(influential) > 0){
  exclusionRows <- rownames(mydata.out)[influential]
  inclusionRows <- !(rownames(mydata.out) %in% exclusionRows)
  mydata.out    <- mydata.out[inclusionRows,]
  reg.last      <- lm(formula = reg.formula, data = mydata.out)
}

cat("Number of removed samples:",dim(mydata)[1]-dim(mydata.out)[1])
## Number of removed samples: 497

Detect the homoscedasticity of residuals.

performance::check_heteroscedasticity(reg.last)
## Warning: Heteroscedasticity (non-constant error variance) detected (p < .001).

Check the independence of residuals with Durbin-Waston’s test.

performance::check_autocorrelation(reg.last)
## OK: Residuals appear to be independent and not autocorrelated (p = 0.302).

The homoscedasticity of residuals dose not satisfy, and the independency is satisfied. Thus, weight MLR will be adopted to solve heteroscedasticity. The weights were inversely proportional to the variance of the dependent variable. Regress the absolute values of the residuals against the fitted values, and the resulting fitted values squared of this new regression will be the desired estimate of this variance.

wt <- 1 / lm(abs(reg.last$residuals) ~ reg.last$fitted.values)$fitted.values^2

Perform weighted least squares regression.

wls.model <- lm(formula = reg.formula, data = mydata.out, weights=wt)

Detect the normality of residuals.

performance::check_normality(wls.model)
## Warning: Non-normality of residuals detected (p < .001).

Plot Figure S1.

Visual inspection did not reveal any obvious deviations from linearity or normality.

performance::check_model(wls.model,check=c('linearity','normality','homogeneity','outliers'))

Compare MLR and weighted MLR

performance::compare_performance(reg.last,wls.model)

Binary logistic regression (BLR)

The diagnostics were processed with the following steps:

  1. Extreme values were detected by the same method as MLR.

  2. Detect multicollinearity by VIF.

  3. The independence of observations by Durbin-Waston’s test.

  4. Check linearity between the log odds and explanatory variables.

  5. Check overdispersion.

  6. Events per variable (EPV).

reg.formula.logi <- update(reg.formula,zPSQI.cat ~ .)
shuimian.logi <- glm(
  formula = reg.formula.logi,
  family  = binomial(link = "logit"),
  data    = mydata
)

Remove outliers.

outlierResult <- car::outlierTest(shuimian.logi)
if (outlierResult$bonf.p[1] < 0.05) {
  exclusionRows   <- names(outlierResult[[1]])
  inclusionRows   <- !(rownames(mydata) %in% exclusionRows)
  mydata.logi.out <- mydata[inclusionRows,]
  logi.last       <- glm(formula = reg.formula.logi,family  = binomial(link = "logit"), data = mydata.logi.out)
} else {logi.last <- shuimian.logi;mydata.logi.out <- mydata}

Remove high leverage points.

leverage.con <- names(which(hatvalues(logi.last) > 
                              3 * length(coefficients(logi.last))/length(fitted(logi.last))))
if (length(leverage.con) > 0) {
  exclusionRows   <- leverage.con
  inclusionRows   <- !(rownames(mydata.logi.out) %in% exclusionRows)
  mydata.logi.out <- mydata.logi.out[inclusionRows,]
  logi.last       <- glm(formula = reg.formula.logi,family  = binomial(link = "logit"), data = mydata.logi.out)
}

Remove influential points.

influential <- which(cooks.distance(logi.last) 
                     > 4/(nrow(mydata.logi.out)-length(logi.last$coefficients)-2))
if (length(influential) > 0){
  exclusionRows <- rownames(mydata.logi.out)[influential]
  inclusionRows <- !(rownames(mydata.logi.out) %in% exclusionRows)
  mydata.logi.out <- mydata.logi.out[inclusionRows,]
  logi.last <- glm(formula = reg.formula.logi,family  = binomial(link = "logit"), data = mydata.logi.out)
}

cat("Number of removed samples:",dim(mydata)[1] - dim(mydata.logi.out)[1])
## Number of removed samples: 408

The independence of observations was performed by Durbin-Waston’s test.

performance::check_autocorrelation(logi.last)
## OK: Residuals appear to be independent and not autocorrelated (p = 0.594).

mydata.logi.out <- mydata.logi.out %>% mutate(
  prob = predict(logi.last,type = 'response'),
  logitP = log(prob/(1-prob))
)

performance::check_model(logi.linear,check=c('linearity'))

Weighted linear mixed model (Weighted LMM)

The regression diagnostics were processed with the following steps:

  1. Multicollinearity.

  2. Outliers.

  3. Homoscedasticity of residuals.

  4. Detect the normality of residuals.

  5. Linearity.

mixed.reg.formula <- as.formula(
  zPSQI ~ gender + age + BMI + NativePlace + OnlyChild + FatherEducationLevel + MotherEducationLevel + FamilyEconomicLevel + MonthlyLivingExpense + PhysicalExercise + RoommateSleepsLate + NoisyDormitory + DormitoryLight + DormitoryHygiene + RelationshipWithClassmates + AmativenessMatter + MedicalMajor + zCDRISC + zMPAI
+ (1 |grade.ord) + (1 |smoking) + (1 |drinking) + (1 |PhysicalHealthStatus.ord) + (1 |MentalHealthStatus.ord) + (1 + RelationshipWithClassmates|AcademicPressure.ord) + (1 + RelationshipWithClassmates|EmploymentPressure.ord) + (1 |ReceivedPsychologicalCounseling))

mixedmodel <- lmer(
  data = mydata
  ,formula = mixed.reg.formula
  ,control = lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa"))

## Warning: Heteroscedasticity (non-constant error variance) detected (p < .001).

Implement weighted LMM. Define weightes as weighted MLR.

wt <- 1 / lm(abs(summary(mixedmodel)$residuals) ~ predict(mixedmodel))$fitted.values^2
mixedmodel.wt <- lmer(
  data     = mydata
  ,formula = mixed.reg.formula
  ,weights = wt
  ,control = lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa")
  )
